  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water spreads grease and oil fires because these substances are less dense than water and can float on its surface. When you pour water onto a grease or oil fire, the water immediately sinks to the bottom due to its higher density. However, the intense heat of the fire causes the water to rapidly vaporize into steam. \n\nThis sudden expansion of steam can cause the burning oil or grease to splatter and spread, potentially igniting nearby surfaces and making the fire worse. Additionally, the steam itself can carry tiny droplets of burning oil, further spreading the flames.\n\nFor this reason, it is crucial to **never use water** to extinguish a grease or oil fire. Instead, you should use a fire extinguisher rated for Class B fires (flammable liquids), smother the flames with a metal lid, or use baking soda or salt to suffocate the fire.",
